<p>And here is an example of how knitting gauge might be written on a yarn =
label.</p>



<p><strong>Knit Gauge (4in x 4in): 18 sts x 24 r on #8 (5mm)</strong></p>



<p>This means a 4-inch by 4-inch square of stockinette fabric should be 18 =
stitches wide and 24 rows tall when knit with size 8 (5mm) knitting needles=
.</p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Why is knitting gauge so important?</h3>



<p>Matching your knitting gauge to the pattern gauge is essential if you wa=
nt your finished project to fit correctly. If your gauge is too loose, your=
 project will be larger than expected; if your gauge is too tight, your pro=
ject will be smaller than expected.</p>



