<p>So, after you finish knitting your swatch, wash it as you would the fini=
shed project. If you=E2=80=99re going to hand wash it, hand wash the swatch=
. If you=E2=80=99re going to run it through the washing machine, run your s=
watch through the same cycle.</p>



<p>And the same advice goes with pinning and blocking. Block your swatch li=
ke you would your finished project. Don=E2=80=99t stretch or pin out your g=
auge swatch if you aren=E2=80=99t going to do the same thing each time you =
wash your sweater. Instead, let it dry flat and relax a bit before taking y=
our gauge measurement.</p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Does knitting gauge&nbsp;<em>really</em>&nbs=
p;have to be exact?</h3>



<p>In general, it=E2=80=99s important to try to match the pattern=E2=80=99s=
 gauge as closely as possible.</p>



<p>True, there may be some knitting projects where it=E2=80=99s not critica=
l to get the exact gauge. For example, you might not mind if your dishcloth=
 or baby blanket is a little bit smaller or larger than it=E2=80=99s suppos=
ed to be.</p>



<p data-slot-rendered-content=3D"true">But, for wearable garments like swea=
ters and hats, it=E2=80=99s important to match the pattern=E2=80=99s gauge.=
 Why? Even a small mismatch can make a big difference in the size of a fini=
shed garment.</p>
