<p><strong>Here=E2=80=99s an example:</strong> Let=E2=80=99s say you want t=
o make a sweater with a 40-inch finished size. If you knit at a gauge of 4 =
stitches per inch, you=E2=80=99ll need to cast on 160 stitches. (4 stitches=
/inch x 40 inches =3D 160 stitches)</p>



<p>But, let=E2=80=99s say your gauge is wrong, and you=E2=80=99re actually =
knitting with a gauge of 4.5 stitches per inch. If you cast on those same 1=
60 stitches, you=E2=80=99ll end up with a sweater with a finished measureme=
nt of 35 =C2=BD inches. (160 stitches =C3=B7 4.5 stitches/inch =3D 35.56 in=
ches) In other words, way too small!</p>



<p>I hope this example illustrates why it=E2=80=99s essential to check your=
 knitting gauge before beginning a project =E2=80=93 especially a garment. =
If the gauge is not correct, the finished project will not fit correctly.</=
p>



