<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Fixing Your Gauge Problems</h2>



<p>Got a problem with your knitting gauge? Here are a few tips to fix a gau=
ge that is too loose or too tight.</p>



<p><strong>Gauge is too tight.</strong>&nbsp;If you have too many stitches =
per inch, your gauge is too tight. To fix this, try using larger needles. L=
arger needles will make larger stitches, and your gauge will be looser.</p>



<p>If larger needles don=E2=80=99t seem to fix the problem, you might actua=
lly need to switch to thicker yarn. For example, if you have been using <a =
href=3D"https://sarahmaker.com/worsted-weight-yarn/">worsted weight yarn</a=
>, try subbing in an Aran weight yarn.</p>



<p><strong>Gauge is too loose.</strong>&nbsp;If you have too few stitches p=
er inch, your gauge is too loose. To fix this, try using smaller needles. T=
his will make your stitches smaller and your gauge tighter.</p>



<p>If smaller needles don=E2=80=99t seem to fix the problem, you can also t=
ry substituting a thinner yarn.</p>



