<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">How do I know if my gauge is off?</h3>



<p>The best way to tell if your gauge is off is to knit a gauge swatch and =
measure it. Compare your measurement to the pattern=E2=80=99s gauge. If the=
y don=E2=80=99t match, then your gauge is off.</p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">What if I can=E2=80=99t match the gauge exac=
tly?</h3>



<p>If you can=E2=80=99t match the gauge exactly, then you need to go up or =
down a needle size and try again. If your gauge is too tight, try larger ne=
edles. Likewise, if your gauge is too loose, try smaller needles.</p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">What if I=E2=80=99m way off?</h3>



<p>Sometimes your gauge can be way off if you=E2=80=99ve substituted a diff=
erent yarn than the one called for in the pattern. In that case, double-che=
ck that the yarn you=E2=80=99ve chosen is the same thickness as the one cal=
led for in the pattern. For example, if the pattern calls for a worsted wei=
ght yarn, you need to use a similar worsted weight yarn.</p>



